[{"category":"section","location":"#OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl:-Optimal-Uncertainty-Quantification","page":"OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl: Optimal Uncertainty Quantification","text":"DISTRIBUTION STATEMENT A. Approved for public release: distribution unlimited. Case Number: AFRL-2024-5455. Cleared 10/2/2024.\n\nThe Optimal Uncertainty Quantification (OUQ) algorithm provides a means of computing the bounds of the expectations of quantities of interest despite not having complete knowledge of the probability distribution of the uncertain variables. This is achieved by finding the worst/best case distributions in some set mathcalA of possible distributions given the knowledge available.\n\nOptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl implements the OUQ algorithm and its convex and \"moment class\" forms in the Julia programming language, using techniques based on complete and rigorous global methods in order to bound the effects of finite computation on the OUQ bounds.","title":"OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl: Optimal Uncertainty Quantification"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl: Optimal Uncertainty Quantification","text":"To install OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl, use the Julia package manager:\n\nusing Pkg\nPkg.add(\"OptimalUncertaintyQuantification\")","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Contributing","page":"OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl: Optimal Uncertainty Quantification","text":"Please refer to the SciML ColPrac: Contributor's Guide on Collaborative Practices for Community Packages for guidance on PRs, issues, and other matters relating to contributing to SciML.\nSee the SciML Style Guide for common coding practices and other style decisions.\nThere are a few community forums:\nThe #diffeq-bridged and #sciml-bridged channels in the Julia Slack\nThe #diffeq-bridged and #sciml-bridged channels in the Julia Zulip\nOn the Julia Discourse forums\nSee also SciML Community page","title":"Contributing"},{"category":"section","location":"#Reproducibility","page":"OptimalUncertaintyQuantification.jl: Optimal Uncertainty Quantification","text":"<details><summary>The documentation of this SciML package was built using these direct dependencies,</summary>\n\nusing Pkg # hide\nPkg.status() # hide\n\n</details>\n\n<details><summary>and using this machine and Julia version.</summary>\n\nusing InteractiveUtils # hide\nversioninfo() # hide\n\n</details>","title":"Reproducibility"}]
